\niOs-\nELY'S CREAM BALM\ns\"s\nRepair Work a Specialty.\n..25 Years of Experience..\nSure to Give Satisfaction.\nGIVES RELICF AT ONCE.\nIt cleanses, soothes, heals and protect* tlio\ndiseased nn'inbriue result in trm Catarrh\narul drives\naway a Cold inth- Hc-qmckl\nRestores the Senses of Taste and SmelL\nEa-v to use. Contains no injurious\nApplied into the nostrils and absorbed.\nS\nSiU so cents at Druggwt. or by\nS. Dqnid Cream Balm for use la\natomizers, 75 cents.\nMOTHERS, WARM ST.\nRECENT CANDIDATE\nFOR GOVERNORSHIP\nTO PUBLISH DAILY\nGeorge W, Egan Will Launch\nThird Newspaper in His\nHome City.\nSioux Falls, S. D., June 18.\u2014'WltWn\n80 dayB there will be a daily newspa\nper published in this city, carrying a\n(Comprehensive news service, possibly\n.covering both evening and morning\nfields, and bearing the name of George\n|W. Egan as publisher and editor.\nThis is the positive statement of\nfriends of the man who was recently\n'defeated for the gubernatorial nomina\ntion in his spectacular race against the\n\u2022opposition of both the progressive and\nstandpat factions of the republican\nparty. It is denied by the friends of\n(Mr. Egan that this is a political ven\niture, but on the other hand It is assert\njed that there is a real need for the pub\nlication and that Egan Is the one man\njwho can command the local support to\ntmake it pay. Being barred from the\n|legal profession, Egan finds it neces\njsary to adopt other means to make his\n(way, and in the publication of the\n'weekly American Republic he has suc\nceeded to such an extent that he feels\njconfident that he can make the daily\nenterprise go well, both locally and\nthroughout the state.\nBack of his project it is understood\nthat there are some of the most sub\nstantial business interests of the city,\nlas well as several capitalists from the\noutside who are willing to join with\nhim in his venture.\nGIRL LASSOES WOLF\nWHILE BEAST SLEEPS\nPierre. S. D., June 18.\u2014Flor\nence March, a Lyman county\ngirl, showed a few days ago,\nwhile herding cattle on the\nprairie that she neither feared\na wolf nor allowed one to es\ncape if possible to get It. She\nsaw a wolf on the prairie, and\nwatched it until it lay down and\nwent to sleep. She then quietly\napproached the sleeping animal\nand threw a rope noose about\nit, and was on her pony dash\ning across the prairie dragging\nher captive before It was fairly\nawake.\nBANQUET IS TENDERED\nTO FORMER DAKOTAN\nHuron, S. D.. June 18.\u2014A banquet\nwas served last night at Hotel Royal,\nI bv employes of the Minnesota, Dakota,\nPierre and Rapid City divisions of the\ni Chicago Northwestern Railway, in\ni honor of Hon. A. C. Johnson, the new\nly appointed traffic passenger manager.\nI /Colonel Dick Woods, of Sioux Falls, was\ntoastmaster, and in introducing Mr.\nJohnson, presented him in behalf of the\nrailroad men with a handsome diamond\nring, after which a number of toasts\nwere given. Among the speakers were\nA.K.Gardner,Dan Glennon, Rev. Father\nDesmond and Mr. Boaldt. Among out\nof town guests present were Wm. Wil\nllsier, superintendent, Winona H. J.\nWagen, general agent, Winona W. B.\nParsons, Winona C. T. Dike, superln\nDoyle, superintendent, Pierre Mr.\nPhelps, division passenger agent, Illin\nois Central, Dubuque, and Mr. Hanson,\npassenger traffic manager, Illinois Cen\ntral, Chicago.\nGRANGE MEETING IS\nHELD AT DRAPER\nDraper, S. D.. June 18.\u2014A great crowd\nattended the Grange picnic and field\nmeet here Monday. A program was\nrendered by the Pomona Grange and\naddresses were given by a number of\nvisiting state Grangers. A basket din\nner was served in the schoolhouse by\nthe ladies.\nOne of the events pulled off was of\nmore than passing interest\u2014the ball\ngame between the hitherto unbeaten\naggregation from Murdo and the Drap\ner team. It was won by Draper after\na hard contest, 12 to 7. During the\ngame, Roy Olson, catcher, suffered\ndouble dislocation of his thumb. The\nbattery for the home team from this\non was Ralph Spears and C. J. Rush\nWATERTOWN ENTERTAINS\nTWO GRAND BODIES\nWatertown, S. D., June 18.\u2014Both of\nthe South Dakota grand lodges, Knights\nof Pythias, and the South Dakota Post\nmasters' league now in session in Wat\nertown report the largest registration\nof delegates in their history. Both\nbodies were at Lake Kampeska last\nnight for an excursion, and a picnic\nsupper and grand ball in the South\nDakota National Guard officers' club\nhouse.\nFALLS 30 FEET, BUT ESCAPES.\nWatertown, S. D., June 18.\u2014Falling\n30 feet onto a cement pavement, Will\nCallon, a bricklayer of this city, mir\naculously escaped death this morning.\nCallon stepped onto a scaffolding that\ngave way beneath him, precipitating\nhim to what seemed certain death by\nthose who witnessed tne accident. Be\nfore they could reach him he picked\nhimself up, and aside from a broken\nbone in one wrist and a few minor\nscratches, Is all right.\n4\nWATERTOWN ATTORNEY\nDISBARRED SIX MONTHS\nPierre, S. D., June 18.\u2014In the\noriginal hearing In the disbar\nmen proceedings against\nCharles H. Schull, of Water\ntown, the supreme court, on the\nfindings of the referee, suspends\nSchull from the rights of an at\ntorney for six months.\nRAILROAD COMMISSION\nRESUMES RATE HEARING\nPierre, S. D., June 18.\u2014The railway\ncommissioners will be In this dtv to\nmorrow to resume the taking of testi\nmony in the 2-cent rate case which\nis pending between the state and the\ndifferent railroads operating in South\nDakota.\nRIGGS PRIZE AWARDEC.\nTftnkton, June 18.\u2014'The annual\nRIggs prize for extempore speaking,\nwas awarded Tuesday afternoon to Mr.\nR. J. Swanson, who spoke on the Taft\nadministration and whether it had\nmade good. In the art department the\nLlvfhgston silver medals were won by\nMiss Margaret Dealy, In the fine arts\ndivision, and* by Miss Margaret Gard\nner, of Bee Heights in the Academy\nclass. Miss Harriett Olson won honor\nary mention in the fine arts, and Miss\nPaulfhe Kolberg, of Fullerville honor\nary mention in th? Academy.\nDOUBLE DIVORCE\nAND QUICK UNiOfl\nSioux Falls, S. D\u201e June IS.\u2014 FclU-w\ning closely upon the divorce of Mrs.\nW. O. Dunham from her husband. Dr.\nW. O. Dunham, of this city, comes the\nannouncement of his mar^age on the\nsucceeding day to Mrs. Mary C. Knapp,\nuntil recently the wife of George\nKnapp.\nTrouble between the members or\nthese two families has been startling,\nfrequent and of the kind which at\ntracts notice by the society which de\ncries it. Dr. Dunham was twice arrested\non complaint of George Knapp, the\nhusband with an alleged grievance, u^\non a statutory charge, once in this city\nand once at Canton. At the latter\nplace it was alleged that Dr. Dunham\nand Mrs. Knapp had registered at a\nhotel in such a manner as :o arouse'\nsuspicion in the inind of the husband\nof the latter. Later Mr. and Mrs.\nKnapp separated and still later Mrs.\nKnapp secured a warrant for the ar\nrest of her husband in Sioux City on\na charge of kidnaping a child born of\nthe two before the craft of the Knapp\nfamily went aground on 0 reef. Th\u00ab\nwarrant was not served, the husband\nsucceeding in getting out of the city\nwith his charge. The child was later\nlocated at some point in Minnesota.\nIt is not understood that there will\nbe any appearance against Dr. Knapp\non the charge originally entered\nagainst him by the husband of the\nwoman who has now become the wife\nof Dr. Dunham. Both families were\nformerly prominent in the social and\nclub life of this city.\nJENKINS FIELD SECRETARY\nFOR DAKOTA WESLEYAN\nWatertown, S. D., June IS.\u2014Rev. J.\nP. Jenkins, D. D., for the past three\nyears pastor of the First Methodist\n\u2022church In this city, has accepted the\nposition of financial secretary of Dak\nota Wesleyan university, at Mitchell,\nnow engaged in raising a $250,000 en\ndowment fund, and will leave Water\ntown as soon as his successor can be\nfound. The Watertown church is one\nof the strongest in the state of the\nMethodists, and Dr. Jenkins is con\nceded to be one of the ablest preacher?\nit has ever had.\nFARMER IS POISONED\nBY CANNED VEGETABLES\nRapid City, S. I)., June 18.\u2014In a tem\nporary trance caused, he believes, by\neating canned vegetables that poisoned\nhim, Sam Gary, a farmer, wandered\nthree days through the country before\nhe recovered his senses. Gary was\ndriving from New Underwood, and\nstopped at a roadhouse for dinner.\nShortly after leaving he became sick'\nand remembers nothing more until he\nfound himself three days later nearly\n10 miles away from his team. What he\ndid or where he went in the lntwval b\u00ab\nis unable to say.\nOFFICER8 SELECTED BY\nSOUTH DAKOTA MASONS\nPierre, S. D., June 18.\u2014Masons in ses\nsion here have selected the following\nofficers: Grand master, Samuel S.\nLockhart, Milbank deputy grand mas\nter, Charles L. Brockway, Chamber\nlain grand senior warden, William J.\nMackin, Terraville grand junior ward\nen. O. H. Williams, Springfield grand\nsecretary, George H. Pettigrew. Sioux\nFalls, S. D. grand treasurer, John C.\nBryan, Plankinton. Chamberlain was\nselected as the meeting place for next\nyear.\nUNION COUNTY MAN\nDIE8 AT YANKTON HOSPITAL\nElk Point, S. D., June 18.\u2014E. A.\nUnw, trt tritn rttr, ttt -mw\ninsane hospital at Yankton Tuesday.\nHe was born at Cabot, Vermont, April\n25, 1843 and came to this county in\n1871. In 1903 his health began to fail\nwhen he was taken to the asylum at\nYankton, at which place he died. He\nleaves a wife and eight children. The\nchildren are Mrs. Anson Goss, of Fair\npoint, S. D. Chester and Lon of this\ncity, William of St. Paul, Minn., Myrtle,\nof Sulpher, S. D. Fred, of Chats\nworth, Iowa Mrs. Olevah Tapp, of\nPortland, Ore., and Mrs. Jennie Brown,\nof Peirre, S. D. He was 67 years old.\nSALOON ROBBED OF $1,700.\nDead wood, S. D., June 18.\u2014Detec\ntives are Investigating the robbery at\nthe Bodega saloon of $1,700. The cash\ntill, in full view of Main street, was\nbroken into and the money taken out.\nThe authorities say they have a clue\nto the thieves.\nELDRIDGE ATTEMPTS TO\nBREAK WESTON RECORD\nReno, Nev., June 18.\u2014Jack Eldredge\nhas left here on the last leg of the\nwalk across the continent from Bos\nton to San Francisco, began March 15,\nto beat Weston's record of 105 days.\nEldredge, who is 24 years old, is now\n19 days ahead of the septuagenarian's\nrecord and expects to reach the coast\nJune 18, 77 days from Boston.\nLast Wednesday he beat Weston's\nbest daily record of 72 miles by three\nmiles, when he made 75 miles in 24\nhours while crossing the desert. Sev\neral Boston sportsmen have wagered\na large sum that the lad will beat\nWeston, and if he succeeds he will be\npaid $2,000.\nMARS IS COMPELLED\nTO\nABANDON HIS TRIP\nTopcka, June 18.\u2014-At 8 o'clock last\nnight J. C. Mars abandoned his Topeka\nto Kansas City aeroplane flight for th(\\\nday at Bismarck, a small town near\nNorth Lawrence.\nAt 7:37 o'clock he made three at\ntempts at Midland, near Bismarck, to!\nresume his flight, but the engine on his'\naeroplane was not working properly\nand darkness compelled him to give up.\nWhether he continues his flight to\nday, he says, depends on whether the\noffer of the $5,000 prize still holds\ngood. If it floes he will continue, but\nif not he probably will abandon th'ij\ncross country flight.\nBOLL WEEVIL ON THE RUN.\nBaton Rouge, La., June 18.\u2014The re\npeated experiments with arsenate of\nlead have proved conclusively that this,\nchemical is the one protection against]\nthe boll weevil is the assertion today\nof Wilmot Newell, secretary of the\nLouisiana crop pest commission.\nSecretary Newell has Issued a bulle\ntin advising\n'*11ton\nplanters to employ^\nthis preparation.\nTH0RNBURG ACQUITTED\nOF\nMURDER CHARGE\nPURPOSE TO DRIVE\nFIVE BIG PACKERS\nOUT OF BUSINESS\nCorporations Alleged to\nrn\nlur-\nburg was fouiel not guilty of the\nder of August Rakowin. The killing\nfollowed a quarre over the settlement\nof an account involving $6. The jury\nheld that Thornburg acted in self de-'\nfense. The fondant was represented\nby M. F. Harri:pton, of O'Neill, and O.\nA. Williams, of this city. W. V. Allen\nassisted County Attorney Rice in the\nprosecution.\nBt\nMerged in National Packing\nCompany, Eliminating\nAll Competition.\nJefferson City, Mo.. June 22.\u2014Attor\nney General Elliott Major began oustei\nproceedings against five meat packing\ncompanies today by filing quo war\nranto informations in the supreme\ncourt. The companies attacked are tho\nArmour Packing company, Morris\nCo., Swift Co., Hammond Packing\ncompany, and St. Louis Dressed Beef\nand Provision company.\nThe Armour, Swift and Morris com\npanies are charged with violating the\nanti-trust law and conspiracy, and the\nHammond and St. Louis Dressed Beef\nand Provision companies, as subsidiary\ncompanies of the National Packing\ncompany, with conspiracy to control the\nbusiness In Missouri.\nThe five companies are named in two\npetitions which ask that the corpora\ntions be excluded from all corporate\nrights, that their licenses be forfeited\nand that all or such portion of their\nproperty as the court may deem proper\nbe confiscated or In lieu thereof a fine\nbe imposed.\nControlled Prices.\nArmour, Swift and Morris are\ncharged with having entered into a con\nspiracy In 1909 to control the prices to\nbe paid by dealers in live stock, poul\ntry, butter, eggs, dairy and agricultural\nproducts, to control the prices to be\npaid by retail and wholesale dealers for\ndressed meats and to control the prices\nto be paid by all retail and wholesale\ndealers for butter, eggs, poultry, game,\ndairy and agricultural products and by\nproducts from the business of slaugh\ntering live stock.\nThe second count of the petition\ncharges that the three packing com\npanies\nconspire,!\nto restrain trade and\ndestroy competition In the purchase\nand sale of meat products, live stock,\npoultry, butter and eggs by fixing a\nprice to be paid by all the members of\nthe alleged agreement and conspiring to\ncontrol the business of buying, selling\nand dealing in packing house products.\nUnlawful Agreement.\nThe alleged absorption of the Ham\nmond and St. Louis Dressed Beef nnd\nProvision companies by the National\nPacking company Is said to have taken\nplace in September, 1902. The Hammond\nand St. Louis companies are charged\nwith having entered into an unlawful\nagreement with others engaged In meat\npacking for the purpose of restricting\ncompetition and prevent lawful trade.\nThe National Packing company, the\nInformation filed in the court today al\nleges, was chartered in New Jersey In\n1902 with a capital stock of $15,000,000\nto engage In meat packing and selling\nand to hold stock of any other corpora\ntion.\nIt is charged In the petition that the\nNational Packing company obtained\ncontrol of the Hammond and St. I^ouls\ncompanies which had previously been\nengaged in Missouri as legitimate com\npetitors and that the National has ever\nsince voted the stock of the companies,\ncollected the dividends and used the\ncompanies In furtherance of the alleged\nunlawful trust.\nSn\nunlawful trust\nAttorney General Major, after he filed\nthe suits, said:\n\"The suits were filed as a result of\nthe examination conducted recently be\nfore former Judge Daniel W. Dillon,\nwho was named by the supreme court\nto preside at the hearings. The Ham\nmond Packing company and the St.\nLouis Dressed Beef and Provision com\npany are owned and controlled in ev\nery matter and detail, both in the pur\nchase of live stock and the sale of\ndressed and finished products, by the\nNational Packing company, of New\nJersey.\n\"The National Packing company, the\nhearing developed. Is owned by three\nbig packers. Swift owns 7-15, Armour\n6-15 and Morris 2-15. While tfoo Na\ntional owns these supposedly independ\nent corporations, it has been holding\nthem out to the public as separate enti\ntles and independent corporations and\ncompetitors in business.\nPrices Regulated.\n\"In this way these corporations have\nbeen and are used as the devices In con\ntrolling the purchase and selling prices.\nIn thus monopolizing the field and in\ncontrolling the packing industry the en\ntrance of new competitors in the busi\nness is practically prohibited.\n\"I have not Instituted suit against\nthe Cudahy Packing company and\nSchwarzchiid Sulzberger, because the\nexamination which I laid was along\ncertain lines and led into a field of in\nquiry which did not disclose whether\nthey were guilty of any violations of\nthe laws.\"\nThe packers must make a return to\nthe suits by June 30. If demurrers are\nfiled they will not be passed upon by\nthe court until the October term. If\nanswers are filed the court may appoint\na commissioner to take evidence before\nadjournment for the summer.\nFIVE YEARS IN MINE\nAS\nMAN, GIRL\nLafayette, Ind., June 22.\u2014Five years\nof hard labor in a quarry, where she\nwas obliged to dress in masculine garb,\ndid not dull the feminine side of Bar\nbara Pring. Taken from bondage there\nand given a chance she fell in love Just\nlike other girls. Today she married\nCharles Paul, a wealthy farmer.\nThe girl's father owns a flint rock\nquarry. At fourteen she was put to\ntvork in the flint bed. dressed in over\nalls and blouse. For five years the girl\ntoiled beside her father. She became\nas strong and capable as any of the\nmen and was treated as they were. La\nfayette people learned of the case and\nreported it to the police.\nThe girl was taken from her father\nand placed in a rescue mission here,\nShe found it difficult at first to wear\nfeminine apparel, but soon learned\nFinally Paul came, then their marriage\nand a honeymoon tour.\nTEDDY WORKS UNTIL\nTIME FOR WEDDING\nNew York, June 22.\u2014As soon aa\nColonel Roosevelt arrived in New York\ntoday he went to the Outlook offices\nwhere he shut himself up with his\nprivate secretary to go through a por\ntion of the accumulation of correspond\nence awaiting him.\nIt was said on his behalf that he\ncould see no callers but would remain\nat work until it was time for him to\ngo to the wedding.\nColonel Roosevelt this afternoon itf\nvited the Rough Riders to attend U\nwedding in a body.\nT- r~ v\n\u00abS\u00a3.Jr\nSENATE APPROVES OF\nTHE RAILRilAD BILL\nFifty Votes Are Given Adminis\ntration Measure\u2014Eleven\nDemocrats Nay*\nWashington, June 21.\u2014By fc it\u00ae\nvoce vote which was practically unan\nimous, the House today, nfter nearly\ntwo hours of discussion, agreed to tile\nconference report on the rail toad bt\nwhich passed the Senate yesterday, o\namendment was offered or adopte I.\nThe bill now goes to the president for\nsignature.\nChairman Hamilton, of the Houtje\ncommittee on territories, announced tq\nday that he would ask the House |o\nconcur all the Senate's amendments\nthe statehood bill.\ncom\nekfng\ncompany, the attorney general charges,\nhave become members ot the alleged\ntrust and have been guilty of abuse of\nprivileges not granted to them by Mis\nsouri.\nise \u00bbo\nnts to\nThe chances of a 'Verdict\" from\nBallinger-Pinchot investigating\nmltteo during the present session \u00aef\ncongress are remote. The rommltteo\nheld a meeting today behind closed\ndoors, but it was announced that an\nadjournment has been taken until ne^t\nin\ntn\ncorn-\nSaturday.\nWashington, June 21.\u2014The senate\nyesterday placed its stamp of approval\non the administration railroad bill,\nwhich has been pending In one stage\nor another almost since the beginning\nof\nthe conference committee on th*t\nmeasure. The vote i ame at the close\nof a day devoted to a fragmentary dis\u00ad\ncussion of\nthe measure, ant! was witl-\nout especial feature. The report pre\nvailed by a large majority, the ayes\nbeing 50 and the nays 11. All of the\nnegative votes were cast by democrat's,\nand Senators Chamberlain, Clay. Mc\nEnery, Simmons. Stone and Taylor\nunited with the republicans in support\nof the bill.\nAnnouncing his Intention of voting\nfor the conference report, Senator\nCummins expressed the opinion th^t\nthe bill reported was as good as the\nSenate bill, if not better. Nevertheless,\nthere were many chances for Improve\nment and the Iowa senator proceeded\nto point them out. His old opposition\nto the commerce court provision first\nfound expression, and he again prophe\nsied undesirable results from the oper\nation of this portion of the law.\nWith reference to the long and short\nhaul provision. Senator Cummins ex\npressed the opinion that under It the\nInterstate Commerce commission would\nhave practical control of the sanation.\nHe thought the railroads would be slow\nto challenge the law because of the\nfear of getting something worse.\nHolds Clause Unconstitutional,\n\"Does the senator consider the lortg\nand short haul provision unconstitu\ntional?\" asked Senator Smoot, abruptly.\nThe Iowa senator confessed that h\u00ab\ndid so regard it.\n\"If that should pro%'e to be the case,'*\ns\nresponded Senator Smoot, \"then ther#\nwill be a provision that there can be n\nquestion about. In that event ther#\nWill be other measures that will not b#!\nto the advantage of the railroals.\"\nSTATEHOOD BILL 18\nPAS8ED BY THE HOU8K\nWashington, June 21.\u2014The statehood\nbill to admit Arizona and New Mexico\nto the union passed the house at 3 it,\nm. It now requires the signature of\nthe president to become law. By a vivft\nvoce vote the House concurred ill the\nSenate amendments to the bill.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nDISTINCTLY BETTER\nCrop News Oontinnea Xncour.\nand the Steel Market\nImproves.\nNew York, June 21. Bradstreet saysi\nIrregularity and relative quiet are\nstill the ruling features in trade and ln\niustry, but evidences of Improvement\nwestern distribution aro rather,\nsharply in contrast with the reports of\nslow trade recently received. Warmer\nweather is the key to the better crop\nand trade reports received this weak\nfrom the vest, northwest and south\nwest, while cool, moist conditions along\nthe Atlantic coast, now disappearing\nhave been a bar to trade and crop de\nvelopments In the east. Relatively\nbest reports come from western cities\nand towns, while country trade, though\nbetter, Is slower to respond, owing to\nfarmers being busy on work delayed.\nR. O. Dunn says:\nCrop news continue encouraging,\nthe\nron and steel market improves, while\nforeign trade now shows an excess of\nexport, and In these three important\nartlculars the business outlook is dis\ntinctly better.\nThe primary dry goods markets dttlt\nreflect light trading, but agents hand\nling cotton goods lines are holding\n1 trices generally firm. Jobbers in\nwestern markets have been shading\nprices at clearance sales to reduc#\nstocks preliminary to stock tak\ning. while announcement is made by\nTO FORCE GOVERNOR\nTO CALL STATE\nWEDS\na\nlarne western house that the usual\nsemiannual clearance sales will be\nomitted on the grounds that the costs\nof replacements are above current val\nues.\nTROOPS\nSan Francisco, t'al.. Juno 21 *-At 10:41\no'clock this morning attorneys for\nLouis Blot Issued a formal statement\nannouncing that the Langford-Kauf\nman fight would be postponed for on*\nweek, or until Saturday, June 26.\nBlot stated that it had been decided\no withdraw the main fight in favor of\na third rate bout to be held Monday\nwith the Intention of forcing the gov\nernor to interfere \"with his troops,\"\nBlot said, after which the matter wouM\nbe taken into court as a test case.. A\nde tsion. he said, would be secured' III\n*8 hours and the \"way cleared for tha\nLar.gford-Kaufmsn fight.\"\nSummoning Louis Blot, the promoter\nof the Kaufman-Langl'ord match, to hie\noffice early today, Chief of Police Mar\ntin told him that lie would not be per\nmitted to proceed wltb the flght. Th\u00ae\nchief advised Blot to discontinue\ntale of tickets.\nthe\nHawarden, la., June 21.\u2014Miss Mary\n\"Shoemaker, daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nG. J. Shoemaker, prominent resident*\n(f this vicinity, was married at 8toux\nFalls, S. D., Wednesday, to T. M. Thorn\nson, of Benson, Minn. After a short\nwedding trip the- couple will make tttOlP\nhome at Benson.\nCenterville. 8. D., June 21.\u2014Andrew\nS Bogue, of this city, who was nomi\nnated nt the primaries last week Iter\nstate's attorney, wjll be married Jtune\nno to Miss Genevieve Cooke, of Pac\nker.","height":"24147","width":"16122"}}
